TAMARA KEITH: You're welcome.

29:42.180 --> 29:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Now: a look at how
the world's
second most populous country is
trying to

29:50.022 --> 29:51.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
deal with pollution.

29:51.857 --> 29:56.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro looks
at how Delhi, India, is trying
to cope with

29:56.862 --> 30:01.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tons of municipal waste in a
city of more
than 20 million.

30:01.733 --> 30:04.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fred's report is part of our
Breakthrough
series.

30:04.236 --> 30:11.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In India's
capital, new
housing sprawls as far as the
eye can see,

30:11.109 --> 30:14.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a symbol of the world's fastest
growing major
economy.

30:14.846 --> 30:20.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There also are towering symbols
of the environmental
cost of all this.

30:20.385 --> 30:23.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Just look for the birds.

30:23.822 --> 30:27.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Under thousands of hovering
vultures are the
city's landfills.

30:27.859 --> 30:34.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is one of three covering
some 70 acres
in a low-income area called
Ghazipur.

30:34.166 --> 30:39.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm standing near the top of the
Ghazipur
landfill site, an accumulation
by now of more

30:39.171 --> 30:41.540 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
than 10 million tons of waste.

30:41.573 --> 30:43.842 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's more than 10 stories high.

30:43.875 --> 30:47.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Behind me, it towers over the
surrounding
skyline.

30:47.312 --> 30:53.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And trucks are all around here,
bringing in
an additional 2,000 tons of
unsorted garbage

30:53.952 --> 30:55.387 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
every day.

30:55.420 --> 30:57.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAHESH BABU, Business Owner: You
can't dump
more in that mountain there.

30:57.989 --> 31:02.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Mahesh Babu
heads an infrastructure
company that's been contracted
by Delhi's

31:02.794 --> 31:07.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government to tackle a trash
problem that
he says is a crisis at many
levels.

31:07.766 --> 31:12.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: Keep in mind Delhi
is on the
seismic zone.

31:12.037 --> 31:13.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, you are really...

31:13.405 --> 31:15.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: If you had
an earthquake
here, God forbid.

31:15.307 --> 31:16.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAHESH BABU: Yes.

31:16.675 --> 31:19.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have an earthquake, you will
have that
mound just sliding down.

31:19.044 --> 31:24.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And even
without an earthquake,
he says the festering garbage is
toxic.

31:24.349 --> 31:30.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Methane from the dump explodes
daily in dozens
of spontaneous fires that spew
toxins into

31:30.322 --> 31:36.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the air, while a stew of heavy
metals and
organic and inorganic pollutants
washes into

31:36.061 --> 31:39.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the soil when it rains and into
Delhi's main
river.

31:39.397 --> 31:43.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: Yes, the dark
liquid right here
is what we call leachate.

31:43.168 --> 31:47.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Babu showed
me a sample
of this so-called leachate.

31:47.239 --> 31:53.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: What we do is
basically treat
it, so that it removes all the
toxic impurities.

31:53.445 --> 32:00.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: But of the
millions of
tons that are not treated yet,
this is the

32:00.552 --> 32:02.621 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stuff that's going into the
Yamuna River.

32:02.654 --> 32:04.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: Especially during
monsoon.

32:04.422 --> 32:09.060 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The
centerpiece of his
company's approach is a year-old
$60 million

32:09.094 --> 32:14.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
power plant that converts waste
to energy,
which is sent to the electric
grid.

32:14.065 --> 32:19.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is ramping up to burn 2,000
tons of trash
per day, which means the city
may not need

32:19.638 --> 32:23.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to add to the landfill, though
it won't immediately
reduce its size.

32:23.508 --> 32:27.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: India has close to
50 cities
which are more than a million
people.

32:27.913 --> 32:32.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, waste energy of this kind
makes a lot
of sense in those kind of
settings.

32:32.484 --> 32:36.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: This isn't
the first attempt
at creating energy from waste.

32:36.755 --> 32:41.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And previous ones haven't
worked, says Delhi-based
environmental activist Sunita
Narain.

32:42.027 --> 32:46.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUNITA NARAIN, Environmental
Activist: The
key reason for failure has been
the inability

32:46.698 --> 32:52.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to sort and segregate the waste
which is then
used for incineration.

32:52.404 --> 32:59.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, if you don't sort and
segregate adequately,
you both have very toxic
emissions that come

32:59.110 --> 33:04.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of the plant, but you also
have very poor
quality of fuel that is
generated.

33:04.549 --> 33:09.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Ideally that
kind of sorting
should happen in homes,
organics, metals,

33:09.754 --> 33:11.456 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
paper and plastics.

33:11.489 --> 33:13.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But Narain says there's a
cultural hurdle.

33:13.692 --> 33:18.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Waste has been the domain of
people on the
lowest rung of the age-old
social hierarchy,

33:18.697 --> 33:22.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or caste system, not the middle
classes who
generate most of it.

33:22.767 --> 33:24.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
SUNITA NARAIN: We are a
caste-ist society.

33:24.936 --> 33:28.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we would like to treat waste
as somebody
else's problems.

33:28.540 --> 33:32.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You get it out of your home, and
then somebody
else deals with it.

33:32.377 --> 33:36.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The state is never asking us to
segregate.

33:36.047 --> 33:39.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it doesn't put the onus and
the responsibility
on households.

33:39.818 --> 33:43.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Instead, the
government
pays a higher rate for
electricity coming

33:43.822 --> 33:48.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of the Ghazipur plant, so
workers can
be hired to segregate the refuse
when it gets

33:48.560 --> 33:49.794 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
here.

33:49.828 --> 33:53.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But once sorted, Babu says,
there's plenty
of added value.

33:53.331 --> 33:57.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: We're looking at
converting biodegradables
into organic fertilizer.

33:57.936 --> 34:01.206 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The combustibles, we convert
into energy.

34:01.239 --> 34:05.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the idea is really to glean
as much value
as possible from this.

34:05.677 --> 34:10.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In time, he
says, there
are plans by his company and
others to chip

34:10.081 --> 34:15.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
away at the landfill and
actually reduce its
size, repurposing some of the
waste as road

34:15.654 --> 34:18.657 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
construction material, for
instance.

34:18.690 --> 34:22.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the plant, combustible trash
is dried and
incinerated.

34:22.460 --> 34:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Babu says the effluent passes
through sophisticated
filters and scrubbers.

34:26.631 --> 34:31.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: Our particulate
matter is less
than 10 parts per million, which
is the standard

34:31.236 --> 34:33.104 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Europe.

34:33.138 --> 34:37.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, because we're located so
close to these
houses here, the idea is to
ensure that whatever

34:37.809 --> 34:41.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
comes out of our stack is
absolutely clean
and clear.

34:41.279 --> 34:45.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Neighbors
invited to the
power plant say they have
already seen an

34:45.050 --> 34:49.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
improvement since it became
operational, a
massive buffer between their
homes and the

34:49.888 --> 34:51.589 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dump site.

34:51.623 --> 34:54.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator):
Before, you got
out of the house and looked at a
huge pile

34:55.026 --> 34:55.994 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of garbage.

34:56.027 --> 34:57.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now we look at this.

34:57.662 --> 35:01.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): It
really was
unbearable during the rainy
season.

35:01.700 --> 35:04.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was so smelly and dirty.

35:04.602 --> 35:06.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now we can even have the door
open and sit
outside.

35:06.938 --> 35:11.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: But for
another nearby
community, the power plant
represents a threat.

35:11.609 --> 35:17.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hundreds of so-called rag
pickers forage for
plastics, glass and any reusable
items they

35:17.315 --> 35:22.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can sell, risking their health
and the wrath
of authorities to eke out a
livelihood.

35:22.320 --> 35:25.857 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not legally supposed to
be here.

35:25.890 --> 35:32.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For them, the company has set up
a preschool
and an arts and craft center.

35:32.664 --> 35:37.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The petals of discarded flowers
from a nearby
florist are used to create
greeting cards

35:37.435 --> 35:38.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and other artwork.

35:38.870 --> 35:43.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mahesh Babu hopes more rag
pickers will choose
the new alternative.

35:43.375 --> 35:47.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He says helping these
marginalized people
is in his company's interest.

35:47.712 --> 35:51.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHESH BABU: We believe that,
unless they
are mainstreamed, the
profitability of the

35:51.983 --> 35:55.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
main project is always under a
cloud.

35:55.053 --> 36:00.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everywhere possible, we have
tried to integrate
people into our mainstream
project itself,

36:01.026 --> 36:03.628 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
so that then they have a sense
of ownership.

36:03.661 --> 36:07.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Otherwise, we have a number of
people who
will and try to bring the
project to a halt.

36:07.665 --> 36:12.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if they are part of the
project, the chances
of success increase
exponentially.

36:12.137 --> 36:17.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In the long
term, he and
environmentalists agree that
projects like

36:17.342 --> 36:22.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this have to succeed, and that
will require
a broad cultural shift.

36:22.213 --> 36:28.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The country has no more room to
bury its trash,
Babu says, and runs of risk of
being buried

36:28.319 --> 36:29.654 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
by it.

36:29.687 --> 36:33.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Fred de Sam
Lazaro in New Delhi.

36:33.458 --> 36:38.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Fred's reporting is a
partnership
with the Under-Told Stories
Project at the

36:38.263 --> 36:45.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
University of St. Thomas in
Minnesota.

36:45.070 --> 36:56.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now: a new book by the one-time
manager of
John F. Kennedy's 1960 campaign
in West Virginia,

36:56.147 --> 37:00.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a founder of the Peace Corps and
the editor
of the storied Washington
Monthly.

37:00.952 --> 37:06.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Charles Peters takes on modern
America in
"We Do Our Part: Toward a Fairer
and More

37:06.257 --> 37:07.959 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Equal America."

37:07.992 --> 37:12.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here again is Judy Woodruff, who
sat down
with Peters recently and asked
him, why this

37:12.564 --> 37:14.399 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
book, why now?

37:14.432 --> 37:16.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES PETERS, Author, "We Do
Our Part: Toward
a Fairer and More Equal
America": I was terribly

37:16.234 --> 37:24.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
concerned about the things that
had taken
us apart, from a country that
was relatively

37:24.843 --> 37:27.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
together during the time I was
growing up.

37:27.512 --> 37:33.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Franklin Roosevelt era, I
would say, lasted
roughly until 1965.

37:33.985 --> 37:41.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not only were incomes becoming
more equal,
but the country was becoming
more equal, in

37:41.426 --> 37:47.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the sense that blacks were
achieving legal
rights that they had never
known.

37:47.065 --> 37:52.203 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And our Jewish prejudice was
radically diminished
by the mid-'60s.

37:52.237 --> 37:56.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And our Catholic prejudice
almost disappeared.

37:56.207 --> 38:01.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it was a country that seemed
to be coming
together.

38:01.346 --> 38:06.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then just a few years later,
the Vietnam
War began to split us apart.

38:06.718 --> 38:11.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You launched a
magazine in
the late 1960s, you said,
because you wanted

38:11.289 --> 38:15.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to look at what the federal
government was
doing right, and what it was
doing wrong,

38:15.160 --> 38:16.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
how it could do better.

38:16.427 --> 38:18.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you soon expanded that to
look at the
whole country.

38:18.663 --> 38:24.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES PETERS: We felt we had
to get into
those broader cultural issues.

38:24.702 --> 38:31.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the main thing that happened
was the snobbery
that began with the anti-war
movement.

38:31.442 --> 38:38.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was, I think, one of two
really bad things
that happened to divide the
country.

38:38.416 --> 38:43.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other was the growth of
greed and the
conspicuous consumption that
fueled the greed.

38:43.655 --> 38:45.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Snobbery.

38:45.223 --> 38:46.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PETERS: Yes.

38:46.758 --> 38:50.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's not a word
that's thrown
out a lot.

38:50.061 --> 38:51.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PETERS: Yes.

38:51.429 --> 38:53.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What did you --
who do you
mean by what happened?

38:53.198 --> 38:58.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES PETERS: In the anti-war
movement,
there was a feeling that the
people who were

38:58.303 --> 39:04.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
against the war were morally
superior to those
who were for the war.

39:04.275 --> 39:10.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I was against the war, but
I understood
there were an awful lot of good
people who

39:10.515 --> 39:12.383 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
believed in the war.

39:12.417 --> 39:18.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's when I began to worry
about what was
going wrong with the anti-war
movement, even

39:18.122 --> 39:20.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
though I was part of the
anti-war movement.

39:20.091 --> 39:23.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You point out a
number of ways
in which the country, for all of
its progress,

39:23.895 --> 39:24.862 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has gone downhill.

39:24.896 --> 39:26.664 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PETERS: Yes.

39:26.698 --> 39:29.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And another way
is, you cite
the greed that you saw crop up
among people

39:29.567 --> 39:35.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Washington who came here
originally to
do public service, but then that
changed.

39:35.039 --> 39:40.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES PETERS: Even though it
contained that
element of snobbery, that was
also a beautiful

39:40.612 --> 39:43.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
element of idealism in the
anti-war movement.

39:43.615 --> 39:46.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that gradually changed in
the '70s.

39:46.951 --> 39:50.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think part of it was simply
these people
were getting older.

39:50.755 --> 39:51.723 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
The V.W.

39:51.756 --> 39:53.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Beetle was no longer the
adequate car.

39:53.625 --> 39:58.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They had to get the station
wagon, and then
they had to get the house.

39:58.396 --> 40:00.164 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But then they got the house.

40:00.198 --> 40:04.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they got -- it had to
be a larger
house, and it had to have a
workout room,

40:04.769 --> 40:09.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it had to have a home
office, and it had
to have walk-in closets and
state-of-the-art

40:09.607 --> 40:11.643 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bathroom and kitchen.

40:11.676 --> 40:16.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, suddenly, people were into
thinking they
needed a lot of money.

40:16.114 --> 40:20.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then they forgot about the
wages paid
to the worker.

40:20.818 --> 40:27.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They became concerned with
increasing their
dividends, meaning increasing
profits.

40:27.191 --> 40:33.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when they read about a plant
closing,
well, that might increase
profit, you know?

40:33.064 --> 40:38.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have got to watch those
wages, because
wages take away from profit.

40:38.503 --> 40:43.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You see running
through this
entire book, Charlie Peters, a
cautionary

40:43.908 --> 40:50.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tale, especially for Democrats,
I think, who
have argued that they are the
party of the

40:50.381 --> 40:56.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working people, that they are
the party of
equal rights, equal access, of
tolerance.

40:56.354 --> 40:57.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PETERS: Yes.

40:57.355 --> 40:58.990 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

40:59.023 --> 41:00.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you're saying
something
was eating away at that from the
inside.

41:00.291 --> 41:01.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHARLES PETERS: Yes.

41:01.292 --> 41:03.227 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

41:03.261 --> 41:09.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The shame of that is, in many
ways, the Democrats
were becoming more inclusive,
more generous.

41:09.801 --> 41:14.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were including the causes
of gays.

41:14.172 --> 41:17.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were including the cause of
immigrants.

41:17.809 --> 41:24.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so they're far more generous
towards those
people than the Republicans in
general.

41:24.615 --> 41:32.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there was much that was
going on that
was in the best of the
Democrats.

41:32.590 --> 41:40.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this failure on wages, the
failure to
concern themselves with the
interest of the

41:40.365 --> 41:42.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
worker, this is where the
liberals failed.

41:42.567 --> 41:48.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Much of the theme
of the book,
it seems to me, is how the
Democratic Party

41:48.206 --> 41:53.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
