43:10.788 --> 43:15.860 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHARLES PETERS: Thank you, Judy.

43:15.893 --> 43:22.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Next: It's called a
picnic, but
instead of hotdogs and potato
salad, this

43:22.800 --> 43:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
one features poetry and music.

43:25.336 --> 43:31.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown met up with its
creator and
master of ceremonies, poet Paul
Muldoon.

43:31.809 --> 43:44.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There was music
from the Irish
musical duo the lost Brothers,
storytelling

43:44.789 --> 43:46.457 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from novelist Nicholson Baker.

43:46.491 --> 43:47.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICHOLSON BAKER, Novelist: I was
in a laundromat.

43:47.492 --> 43:50.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It was a laundromat in
Marseille, France.

43:50.094 --> 43:51.062 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Marseille.

43:51.095 --> 43:52.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do you hear that?

43:52.296 --> 43:54.899 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a mattress of a word.

43:54.932 --> 43:59.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EILEEN MYLES, Poet: This one's
basically talking
to my computer.

43:59.103 --> 44:01.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And there was
poetry by Eileen
Myles.

44:02.006 --> 44:03.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EILEEN MYLES: You.

44:03.875 --> 44:06.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After all these years, you
should know my
font.

44:06.210 --> 44:10.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You should know the numbers go
in the middle.

44:10.314 --> 44:12.183 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What'd I say?

44:12.216 --> 44:17.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Muldoon's Picnic
is an old-fashioned
variety show, the brainchild of
poet Paul

44:17.522 --> 44:20.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Muldoon, held monthly at the
Irish Art Center
in Manhattan.

44:20.324 --> 44:25.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON, Muldoon's Picnic:
While our
drugs of choice were run from
Istanbul through

44:25.196 --> 44:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a girl called Joyce, whose real
name was Mule.

44:28.966 --> 44:31.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what's your
role here?

44:31.402 --> 44:33.271 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You're sort of the impresario?

44:33.304 --> 44:35.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: Sort of impish
impresario.

44:35.840 --> 44:37.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Impish, yes.

44:37.508 --> 44:40.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL MULDOON: Of course,
everyone is stuck
in their own little world these
days.

44:40.845 --> 44:46.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has to do with people
making their own
amusement, or at least opening
themselves

44:46.918 --> 44:56.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the possibility, I suppose,
of amusement
being of a somewhat more direct
nature, you

44:56.761 --> 45:00.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
know, the poem, the short story,
the song.

45:00.765 --> 45:07.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Muldoon is an
Irish-born, renowned
Pulitzer Prize-winning poet,
Princeton Professor,

45:07.371 --> 45:12.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
poetry editor of "The New
Yorker," and front
man for the band Rogue Oliphant.

45:12.243 --> 45:17.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Picnic revives a popular New
York vaudeville
variety show from the 1880s.

45:17.815 --> 45:23.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it begins with an even older
tradition
of poetry as an oral art form to
be performed.

45:23.287 --> 45:29.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: Certainly, in the
Irish tradition,
there is no distinction, for
example, between

45:29.360 --> 45:30.861 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the poem and the song.

45:30.895 --> 45:37.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many of the great poems in the
Gaelic tradition
were, coincidentally, songs.

45:37.168 --> 45:44.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What's the
difference between
writing lyrics for a song and
writing a poem?

45:44.175 --> 45:48.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: They're akin as
activities,
but they're distinct.

45:48.879 --> 45:51.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're both using words,
obviously.

45:51.549 --> 45:58.189 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, the song lyric is missing
something.

45:58.222 --> 46:06.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's missing an element, which
will bring
it to its -- what it most may be
in the world.

46:06.364 --> 46:08.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's the music.

46:08.065 --> 46:14.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, to try to write a song lyric
is difficult
for me, and I think many people,
because,

46:14.905 --> 46:19.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when I'm writing a poem, my
impulse is to
be perfect, is to achieve
perfection.

46:19.477 --> 46:20.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Which means what?

46:21.012 --> 46:23.648 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: Which means that
it is unassailable.

46:23.681 --> 46:27.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is -- there is not a word out
of place
in it.

46:27.718 --> 46:30.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And it doesn't
need music to
complete it.

46:30.421 --> 46:35.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: It doesn't need
music, because
some wise wag once said it
brings its own

46:35.426 --> 46:37.294 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
music.

46:37.328 --> 46:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Muldoon's poetry
is famously
filled with its own music,
metaphors and allusions.

46:42.466 --> 46:46.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A new selected poems was
recently published.

46:46.237 --> 46:48.739 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I asked what effect he strives
for.

46:48.773 --> 46:55.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: Contrary to what I
think many
people feel, many people feel
art is about

46:55.613 --> 46:58.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
salve, about peace.

46:58.282 --> 47:02.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I myself am looking for
something quite different.

47:02.787 --> 47:04.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm looking for trouble.

47:04.955 --> 47:06.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm looking for...

47:06.257 --> 47:08.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: No rest, not
rest, trouble.

47:08.793 --> 47:14.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL MULDOON: Well, you know,
trouble is the
mode of the world.

47:14.098 --> 47:18.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the mode of the world, and
to be equal
to the mode of the world, I
think, in a strange

47:18.669 --> 47:28.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way, to be able to represent
unrest, and to
be able to bring together the
elements, the

47:28.279 --> 47:36.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chemical components that, when
they combine,
do have some kind of combustion.

47:36.087 --> 47:44.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And at Muldoon's
Picnic, you
can get your poetry with a
musical performance.

47:44.395 --> 47:50.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the Irish Art Center in
Manhattan, I'm
Jeffrey Brown for the "PBS
NewsHour."

47:50.835 --> 47:57.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The next performance
of Muldoon's
Picnic will be held in New York
a week from

47:57.541 --> 47:59.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
